{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016AxAX4kv1bjJY8reGWgqKv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1: The review input is scoped to the lines that changed, not the full content of each modified file.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about how the diff is parsed/filtered. The failure is in the logic that scopes input to changed lines. This could be a Unit test on the diff-parsing function.\n- REAL-INFRA: Does this need real OS/network? No — you can feed a fake diff string to the parsing function.\n- MOCK-HIDE: Would mocking hide failure? No — you can test the actual parsing logic with a fake diff.\n- LLM-DEP: No LLM dependency here — this is about what data is passed to the LLM, not LLM output quality.\n\n\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nThis is Unit — testing the function that extracts/scopes changed lines from a diff.\n\n**Behavior 2: Inline comments are attached to the correct positions in the diff view on the pull request.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This involves the mapping from LLM findings to diff positions AND the GitHub API call to post at specific positions. The failure could be in the position calculation logic itself (Unit) or in the actual GitHub API accepting and displaying the position (System - real HTTP). Since the behavior requires the comments to show up correctly in the actual PR, I need to verify both the calculation and the real GitHub integration.\n\n- REAL-INFRA: The core question is whether mocking the API is enough to catch failures. I can test the position mapping logic with Integration tests by verifying the correct position number gets sent, but that doesn't guarantee GitHub will render it correctly. The behavior explicitly requires the attachment to appear in the diff view, so I likely need System tests with real GitHub API calls to fully validate this.\n\n- REJECTION-GATE: An Integration test with mocked GitHub API would catch calculation errors in the position mapping, but it won't verify the end result actually displays correctly on the PR. Since the requirement is about the inline comments appearing at the right positions in the diff view itself, System testing seems necessary.\n\nI'm leaning toward System minimum because the behavior is about the visible result on GitHub, not just the parameter being calculated correctly.\n\nNow looking at Behavior 3: whether the agent identifies a real defect in a PR with a known bug. This is fundamentally about LLM detection quality — a mock wouldn't help here since the core requirement is that the model actually finds the bug.\n\nFor Behavior 4, I'm checking if every finding in the summary has a matching inline comment posted. This is a consistency invariant between two outputs, which I can verify with mocked GitHub APIs without needing real infrastructure. The LLM generates the findings themselves, so I need to verify the findings are consistent across both places. generated findings are posted both as inline and summary, we could use a stubbed LLM response. But wait — if the LLM generates findings and the code is supposed to post all of them both ways, we need the LLM to generate some findings. We can stub the LLM output.\n\nActually, the real invariant here is whether the code posts the same findings list to both inline comments and the summary. This is a coordination property between modules — the failure would be if they diverge. This looks like an Integration test: I'd mock the LLM to return specific findings, mock the GitHub API, and verify both posting paths use the same data. The consistency doesn't depend on LLM quality, just on correct routing.\n\nFor the full end-to-end sequence — reading the diff, posting inline comments, and posting the summary — that's explicitly about a real pull request, so it requires real GitHub infrastructure.\n\nThe sequence involves multiple real steps: reading the diff from GitHub, calling the LLM to identify problems, posting inline comments, and posting the summary. That's a full workflow with real dependencies on both GitHub and the LLM. So the minimum level here is Workflow.\n\nMapping it all out: Unit tests handle the parsing logic, System tests verify the GitHub API interactions, Agentic tests depend on real LLM quality, Integration tests check consistency between modules, and Workflow tests run the full end-to-end sequence on a real pull request.\n\nNow I'm assigning probability distributions across the test levels for each behavior. Behavior 1 is mostly a Unit test with some Integration possibility. Behavior 2 heavily favors System since it needs real GitHub to verify the position in the diff view. Behavior 3 is clearly Agentic because it depends on LLM quality. Behavior 4 is Integration-focused, checking consistency between components.\n\nFor Behavior 5, the Workflow level dominates since it orchestrates the full end-to-end flow. Looking at plan consistency, each behavior's test description aligns with its intended level—Unit tests the parsing logic in isolation, System validates against real GitHub, Agentic uses a real LLM on a known bug, and Integration wires the components together.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10002,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10002},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"da5ef526-ace9-4416-8ad6-cb2a505d0177","uuid":"045555dc-8add-401f-bd8c-de95e70d5032"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016AxAX4kv1bjJY8reGWgqKv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01QiciBKWgGqYCG212XTnELd","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The review input is scoped to the lines that changed, not the full content of each modified file.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is entirely in the diff-parsing/scoping logic — a function that takes raw diff or file content and returns only changed lines. This is a single algorithmic boundary with no I/O. REAL-INFRA: A fake diff string is sufficient; no real GitHub call is needed to expose a bug where the full file is passed instead of changed lines. MOCK-HIDE: Nothing needs to be mocked — the function can be called directly. LLM-DEP: No LLM output quality involved; this is about what data is fed as input. MULTI-STEP: Single function. REJECTION-GATE: Integration was considered but rejected — the failure mode does not require multiple modules to interact; it appears in the line-filtering function alone.","test_description":"Given a synthetic unified diff string containing both context lines and changed (+/-) lines for a multi-file patch, call the diff-scoping function directly and assert that its output contains only the added/removed line content, not unchanged context lines or lines from unmodified files.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Inline comments are attached to the correct positions in the diff view on the pull request.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure boundary spans two concerns: (a) calculating the correct diff position number and (b) GitHub rendering that number at the right location in the diff view. REAL-INFRA: GitHub's diff position numbering is a GitHub-specific convention tied to how GitHub computes hunk offsets. An in-process mock that accepts any position integer will always pass even when the calculated value is wrong; only a real GitHub API call and inspection of where the comment actually appears exposes off-by-one or hunk-boundary errors. MOCK-HIDE: A mocked HTTP client verifies only that some position integer was sent — it cannot verify GitHub rendered the comment at the right line. REJECTION-GATE: Integration was considered but rejected because the phrase 'in the diff view on the pull request' makes correctness observable only through the real GitHub rendering, not through verifying the outgoing parameter value.","test_description":"Create a real test PR in a controlled GitHub repository with a known patch (e.g., a two-hunk diff with a specific added line). Run the comment-posting module against that PR. Then use the GitHub API to retrieve posted review comments and assert that each comment's `position` and `path` fields match the expected hunk offset of the target line, and that the comment appears at the correct line when the PR diff view is fetched.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.62,"Agentic":0.09,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The agent identifies at least one real defect in a pull request that contains a known introduced bug.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: 'Identifies at least one real defect' is entirely a statement about LLM output quality. A deterministic stub that always returns a canned finding will always pass this assertion regardless of whether the real model would catch the bug. The test must run the real LLM to expose failures like prompt regressions, model updates, or edge-case bugs the model misses. MOCK-HIDE: Any stub LLM trivially satisfies this behavior. REAL-INFRA: The PR diff could be provided as a fixture string, so real GitHub is not strictly required — only the real LLM call is. MULTI-STEP: Detection is a single inference step, not a chain. REJECTION-GATE: System was considered (real GitHub diff fetch) but the behavior's failure is about detection quality, not HTTP plumbing — a fixture diff is sufficient to isolate that.","test_description":"Prepare a fixture diff that introduces a known, unambiguous bug (e.g., an off-by-one in a loop bound or a missing null check). Pass this diff directly to the real LLM-backed defect-identification function and assert that the returned findings list contains at least one item whose description or location references the introduced bug.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Every finding listed in the top-level summary corresponds to an inline comment that was also posted — no findings appear in the summary without a matching inline comment.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is a coordination bug between the module that collects findings, the module that posts inline comments, and the module that builds the summary. This only appears when multiple modules are wired together — it cannot be caught by testing any single function. REAL-INFRA: The invariant is about internal data routing, not real HTTP responses. A stub GitHub API that records all posted comments and a stub LLM that returns deterministic findings are sufficient to expose any divergence in the finding lists used for inline vs. summary posting. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking individual modules (LLM or HTTP) in isolation hides the coordination failure, but an integration harness that wires all modules together with stubs catches it. LLM-DEP: Correctness of this invariant does not depend on LLM output quality — any deterministic stub finding list exercises the routing logic. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network needed — stub HTTP catches mis-routing. (b) No real LLM needed — routing bug is independent of model quality. (c) No chained agentic steps.","test_description":"Wire the full pipeline (diff-scoper → stub LLM returning 3 known findings → inline-comment poster → summary-comment poster) against a stub HTTP client that records all API calls. After running, collect the finding identifiers from all recorded inline comment payloads and from the recorded summary comment payload. Assert the two sets are equal — no finding appears in the summary that lacks a corresponding inline comment call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full sequence — reading the diff, posting inline comments, posting the summary comment — completes correctly for a real pull request without manual intervention.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: The behavior explicitly names a sequence of distinct agentic steps: (1) read the diff from a real PR via real GitHub API, (2) run LLM-based defect analysis on that diff, (3) post inline comments back to the real PR, (4) post the summary comment. Each step has its own real I/O or real LLM call. REAL-INFRA: 'For a real pull request' directly requires real GitHub HTTP. LLM-DEP: The analysis step requires a real LLM call, making the overall sequence non-deterministic. Combined, these are multiple real agentic steps in sequence, satisfying the Workflow definition. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic was considered but rejected because the behavior explicitly requires multiple sequential steps each with real I/O — the failure modes include timing, state hand-off between steps, and partial failure recovery, none of which a single-step Agentic test exercises.","test_description":"Create a controlled test PR in a sandboxed GitHub repository containing a small diff with a known introduced bug. Invoke the full automation pipeline end-to-end with no mocks. Assert that: (a) at least one inline review comment appears on the PR pointing to the changed file, (b) a top-level PR comment exists containing a findings summary, and (c) no uncaught exception or manual prompt was required during execution.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.15,"Workflow":0.75}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10002,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10002},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"da5ef526-ace9-4416-8ad6-cb2a505d0177","uuid":"5575f0de-a911-4f4f-97ed-001fe22b0869"}
